cessary to write a chapter on the emperor who, in effect, personally dominated and governed the country throughout his reign; to add a section on the imperial family, the ministers, and some other high officials to an account of the intellectuals who supported the state; and to sketch the application of Official Nationalty both in home affairs and in foreign policy. In this manner this title is able to bring the state doctrine and its role in Russian history into proper focus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNationalismzSoviet Union. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  a19th century.  aautocracy.  aautocrat.  abiographical.  aeuropean history.  agovernment and politics.  agovernment officials.  ahistorical.  aideological.  aimperial family.  anationalities.  anationality.  anicholas i.  anonfiction.  aofficial nationality.  aorthodoxy.  arussia.  arussian emperor.  arussian foreign policy.  arussian history.  arussian intellectuals.  arussian ministers.  arussian policies.  arussian rulers.  aslavs.  asocial cultural.  asociology.  atsar.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052001065940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520341449?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520341449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520341449/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY